local glossary = {

	"Gross Sales - A measure of overall sales before adjustment for customer discounts, returns, and allowances; is calculated simply by adding all sales invoices, and not including other charges such as taxes in the total.",

	"Net Sales - The amount a seller receives from the buyer after costs associated with the sales are deducted - including merchandise returned for credit, allowances for damaged or missing goods, freight out, and any cash discounts allowed.",

	"Cash - Legal tender or coins that can be used to purchase goods or services, or satisfy debt. In accounting, cash is considered on the balance sheet as cash, and also cash equivalents, including assets that can be converted into cash within 90 days - such as bank deposits or marketable securities, such as government bonds and banker's acceptances.",

	"Revenue - Revenue is the amount of money from sources including operating and investing activities earned in a given period, including discounts and deductions for returned merchandise. For any specific period, it is the \"top line\" or \"gross income\" figure from which costs are subtracted to determine net income. In the case of government, revenue is the money received from taxation, fees, fines, inter-governmental grants or transfers, securities sales, mineral rights, and resource rights, plus any sales that are made.",

	"Expenses - Expenses are the opposite of income. The expenditures of a firm distributed in the course of continuing and facilitating ongoing operations.  Expenses are subtracted from Revenue to determine Net Income.",

	"Net Profit (Loss) - The results of subtracting Expenses from Revenue for any given period; when the figure is positive, it is called Net Income, when negative, it is called Net Loss.",

	"Contract - A contract is a legally binding document in which parties agree to exchange a 'performance', a service or good, for a 'consideration', or an agreed upon price.",

	"Fiscal Policy - Government spending policies that influence economic conditions. These policies may include the manipulation of tax rates, interest rates, and government spending, in an effort to control the economy.",

	"Assets - Resources having economic value, owned or controlled by an individual, corporation or country, with the expectation that it will provide future benefit.",

	"An asset is a balance sheet item on a financial statement that represents something a business owns that it uses produce revenue; including cash and cash equivalents, property, plant, and equipment, inventory, and supplies.  In the context of financial statements, assets are either current or long-term. Current means that the asset will be consumed within one year. Generally this includes things like cash, accounts receivable and inventory. Long term assets are those that are expected to keep on providing benefit for more than one year, such as property, plant, and equipment.  In accounting, the dollar total amount number of assets must be equal to that of the combination of a corporation's liabilities and its owner equity at any point in time.",

	"Liabilities - Claims on a company that represent debts or obligations created during the course of business operations, that the company must meet in the future.  In accounting, a liability is a balance sheet item that represents claims on a company's resources -- including loans, accounts payable, mortgages, deferred revenues and accrued expenses. In the context of financial statements, Current liabilities are debts payable within one year, while long-term liabilities are debts payable over a longer period.  In accounting, at any one moment in time, dollar total amount of liabilities must be equal to the difference between those of owner equity, and the company's total assets.  Owner's Equity (also, 'shareholder's equity') - The total amount of resources that belong to a business's owners.  It is the total of the funds contributed by the owners (the stockholders) plus the retained earnings (or losses) of the corporation. In general, equity is the ownership of any asset after all debts associated with that asset are paid off.  In accounting, at any one moment in time, the dollar total amount of owner's equity must be equal to the difference the company's total assets and its liabilities.",

	"Profit Margin - A ratio of profitability calculated as net income divided by revenues, or net profits divided by sales. It is a measure of how much out of every dollar of sales a company actually retains as earnings.  Profit margin is displayed as a percentage; a 10% profit margin, for example, means a company has a net income of $0.10 for each dollar of sales.",

	"Merchandise Inventory - Merchandise inventory are goods that a company has on hand for sale to its customers.  Inventory is recorded as an asset on a company's balance sheet.",

	"Balance Sheet - A financial statement that summarizes a company's assets, liabilities and owners' equity at a specific point in time.  The Balance Sheet is a financial statement that gives readers an idea as to what the company owns and owes, as well as the amount that has been invested by its owners (shareholders).  The balance sheet must always conform to the following formula:   Assets = Liabilities + Shareholders' Equity Each of the three segments of the balance sheet will have many accounts within it, that reflect the value of each. The exact accounts on a balance sheet will differ by company and by industry.",

	"Financial Statements -  A written report which quantitatively describes the financial position of a company. This includes an income statement and a balance sheet, and often also includes a statement of cash flows. Financial statements are usually compiled on a quarterly and annual basis.",

	" ",
}

return glossary